File: e2e/helpers.ts, lines 433-441.

The cleanup() function chains 5 async calls sequentially without guards:
```
const cleanup = async () => {
  await client.close();
  await finalContext.close();
  await finalServer.kill();
  await finalTestSrv.kill();
  fs.rmSync(tmpDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
  ...
};
```

If `finalContext.close()` throws (e.g., Chromium crashed), `finalServer.kill()` and `finalTestSrv.kill()` are never called, leaving orphaned Node processes. The temp directories also leak.

The fix: wrap each async call with .catch(() => {}). The existing catch block on lines 444-452 already does this correctly — follow the same pattern for the happy-path cleanup.

Fixed cleanup should look like:
```
const cleanup = async () => {
  await client.close();
  await finalContext.close().catch(() => {});
  await finalServer.kill();
  await finalTestSrv.kill();
  fs.rmSync(tmpDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
  fs.rmSync(finalCleanupDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
  cleanupTestConfigDir(configDir);
};
```

Note: client.close() and server.kill()/testSrv.kill() already have internal try/catch guards (verified in fixtures.ts), so they never throw. The only call that can throw is context.close() (Playwright BrowserContext.close). Adding .catch(() => {}) to context.close() is sufficient, but adding it to all async calls is defensive and consistent with the catch block pattern.

Do NOT modify the catch block on lines 444-452 — it is already correct.

Files:
- e2e/side-panel-data-flow.e2e.ts — 2 finally blocks (around lines 340 and 448)
- e2e/side-panel-icons.e2e.ts — 2 finally blocks (around lines 94 and 170+)

The pattern in each finally block looks like:
```
} finally {
  await context.close();      // can throw if browser crashed
  await server.kill();
  await testServer.kill();
  fs.rmSync(cleanupDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
  cleanupTestConfigDir(configDir);
}
```

Fix: Add .catch(() => {}) to the `await context.close()` call:
```
} finally {
  await context.close().catch(() => {});
  await server.kill();
  ...
}
```

Also add .catch(() => {}) to `await mcpClient.close()` where it appears before context.close() in the side-panel-data-flow.e2e.ts animation test (line 449) — mcpClient.close() is already internally guarded but adding the catch is consistent.

Do NOT change the order of cleanup calls or add/remove any cleanup steps. The fix is purely adding .catch(() => {}) guards.
